a_{n}=1+\frac{1}{2}+\cdots+\frac{1}{n}-\log(n)\  \text{ converges.}
 \log k - \log(k-1) = \int_{k-1}^k \frac{dt}t \\ \int_k^{k+1}\frac{dt}t <\frac 1k < \int_{k-1}^k \frac{dt}t  \\ \log(n+1) - \log 2 < \sum_{k=2}^n \frac 1k <\log n \\ 1-\log 2<1-\log 2 + \log(n+1)-\log n < \sum_{k=1}^n \frac 1{k} -\log n < 1 
 a_{n}-a_{n-1} = \frac 1n  - \log{n}+ \log(n-1) =\frac 1n - \int_{n-1}^n\frac{dt}t<0 
